NABATAEAN AGRICULTURE (KITAB AL-FILAHA AL-NABATIYYA)
Language: Arabic (العربية)
Script: Arabic
Target: Ibn Wahshiyya's claimed translation of pre-Islamic Mesopotamian texts on agriculture, ritual, and cosmology
SEARCH INSTRUCTIONS
Search in Arabic. This is a SINGLE TEXT but a massive and understudied one. Use:
Core terms:

كتاب الفلاحة النبطية (Kitab al-Filaha al-Nabatiyya — the Nabataean Agriculture)
ابن وحشية (Ibn Wahshiyya — the translator/compiler, 9th-10th century)
النبط / الأنباط (al-Nabat / al-Anbat — the Nabataeans, but in this context = the pre-Islamic Mesopotamian population)
الكلدانيون (al-Kaldaniyyun — the Chaldeans)
الكسدانيون (al-Kasdaniyyun — another term for ancient Babylonians)

Functional search terms:

عبادة الكواكب والنجوم (worship of planets and stars) → Governance structure
الأصنام والطلسمات (idols and talismans) → Watcher technology?
الزراعة المقدسة (sacred agriculture) → Loyal-faction teaching (agriculture = independence)
الطقوس القديمة / الطقوس البابلية (ancient rituals / Babylonian rituals)
أرواح الأرض / الجن في الأرض (spirits of the earth / jinn in the earth) → Pre-human species
النبوة عند النبط (prophecy among the Nabataeans)
الطوفان / الطوفان العظيم (the flood / the great flood) → Narrative Beat #5

SPECIFIC QUESTIONS

Authenticity assessment: Scholarly opinion is divided — some say Ibn Wahshiyya genuinely translated ancient Mesopotamian texts, others say he fabricated. Search for the CURRENT state of the debate in Arabic scholarship. Does the text contain verifiable Mesopotamian material (agricultural practices, astronomical observations, religious details) that couldn't have been fabricated in the 9th century?
The cosmological system: What cosmology does the Nabataean Agriculture describe? Is there a creator figure? A pantheon? A hierarchical governance structure? Multiple species of beings?
Pre-flood knowledge: Does the text describe knowledge or civilization before a catastrophe? Preservation of knowledge? Pillars or tablets buried before the flood?
The cult of the seven planets: The Nabataean Agriculture is connected to the Harranian Sabian tradition. Does it describe planetary worship in terms that map to our territorial governance framework?
Agricultural knowledge as sacred knowledge: The title itself connects agriculture to a spiritual tradition. Is agriculture framed as DIVINE TEACHING? If so, by whom was it taught? This would map to the loyal-faction curriculum (agriculture = principles for independence, absent from the rebel Hermon curriculum).
Ritual practices: Any description of ritual practices that map to the frameworks we've identified — consciousness-alteration, entity-contact, soul-transit, substance-use?
Names and beings: Any named beings in the text — gods, spirits, demons, teachers — that we can map by function to the Entity Unification Key?


